# One Component Per File

Every React component must live in its own file. Do not define more than one
component in a single file, even small presentational helpers.

- The file exports exactly one component; its props type lives alongside it.
- Name the file after the component (`TokenBalanceRow.tsx` → `TokenBalanceRow`).
- A folder's entry component goes in `index.tsx`; sibling components each get
  their own file in the same folder and are imported where needed.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - two components in one file
export const Wallet = () => {
  return <TokenBalanceRow symbol="LTCA" balance="0" chainLogo={logo} />;
};

const TokenBalanceRow = ({ symbol, balance, chainLogo }: TokenBalanceRowProps) => {
  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
};
```

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD - TokenBalanceRow.tsx
type TokenBalanceRowProps = {
  symbol: string;
  balance: string;
  chainLogo: React.ReactNode;
};

export const TokenBalanceRow = ({ symbol, balance, chainLogo }: TokenBalanceRowProps) => {
  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
};

// ✅ GOOD - index.tsx
import { TokenBalanceRow } from './TokenBalanceRow';
```
